# Transaction Support Analyst (Accounting Firm)

## Overview
Transaction Support Analysts work within Advisory/Deals divisions of Big Four accounting firms, providing financial due diligence and analysis services for M&A transactions, capital raises, and restructurings for private equity funds and corporate clients.

## Core Responsibilities
- Analyze historical financial performance, quality of earnings, working capital, and cash flow of target companies in M&A transactions to identify underlying trading performance
- Build comprehensive financial models and perform valuations using DCF, comparable company analysis, and precedent transactions to support deal pricing and structure decisions
- Assess business models, revenue drivers, competitive positioning, and growth opportunities through commercial analysis of target companies and their market environments
- Identify financial and commercial risks including accounting adjustments, customer concentration, and operational issues that could impact transaction value or terms
- Prepare vendor due diligence information packages for sellers and comprehensive due diligence reports for buyers, synthesizing complex financial analysis into clear insights
- Support clients through deal negotiations by analyzing offer terms, price adjustments, and transaction structures while coordinating with lawyers and financial advisors

## Key Skills Required

### Technical Skills
- Advanced Excel modeling including complex formulas, pivot tables, and financial statement analysis
- Accounting knowledge of AASB standards, financial statement interpretation, and earnings adjustments
- Financial analysis including ratio analysis, trend analysis, margin analysis, and valuation concepts
- Understanding of M&A processes, transaction structures, and data room platforms like Ansaira and Intralinks

### Interpersonal Skills
- Exceptional attention to detail and accuracy when analyzing financial data and preparing client deliverables
- Strong time management skills to handle tight deadlines across multiple concurrent deal projects
- Clear written and verbal communication to synthesize complex information for client presentations
- Professional demeanor in client meetings, team collaboration, and intellectual curiosity for problem-solving

### Commercial & Regulatory Awareness
- Commercial awareness of business models, revenue drivers, cost structures, and industry dynamics
- Understanding of Australian Corporations Act, ASIC oversight, FIRB requirements, and ACCC competition rules

## Work Mode

### Analytical Work (60-70%)
Excel financial modeling, quality of earnings analysis, working capital calculations, revenue trend analysis, data extraction from data rooms, report drafting, documentation of findings, and quality control checks of analysis.

### Meetings & Client Interaction (15-25%)
Daily team stand-ups, management presentations with target companies, client update calls and site visits, weekly team meetings, internal training sessions, and participating in Q&A sessions during active deal processes.

### Research & Learning (10-15%)
Industry and market research on target companies and competitors, reading prior deal reports for reference examples, attending internal technical training, reviewing guidance materials, and staying current on M&A market trends.

### Project Coordination (5-10%)
Coordinating information flow between clients, target management, legal advisors, and other transaction parties, maintaining organized working papers, managing data requests, and tracking project timelines and deliverables across deals.

### Business Development & Administration (0-5%)
Junior analysts have minimal business development duties but support partners in pitch preparation, complete timesheet tracking, maintain professional development records, and contribute to practice development initiatives.

## Workplace Culture
Project-based work with tight deal-driven deadlines, typically managing 3-5 concurrent deals lasting 4-12 weeks each. Better work-life balance than investment banking with typical hours 8:30am-6:30pm.

## Career Path
- Entry: Graduate/Junior Analyst (0-2 years) - financial analysis and report drafting
- Progression: Senior Analyst (2-5 years) → Manager (5-8 years) → Senior Manager/Director (8-12 years) → Partner (12+ years)

